{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2975abb-73c8-4d11-b618-b4c301054b60","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType` must be `Exe` | Tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the two critical properties that make a console app installable as a `dotnet tool`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c7cd273-5a1e-4cdc-82ea-1dffd98e301e","outputTokens":474,"requestId":"CC23:281228:C0AB84:DF4502:69EAC1CF"},"id":"801d2c93-cc87-41dc-9ec5-171053bcb6c6","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:05:28.727Z","parentId":"2c014335-1d09-4f63-915e-c995da3d1f2b"}
